<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-681-206  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 681 206.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 18 1989 n237 p136(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>No silver bullet. (no easy assessment of information systemsvalue)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McLean, Ephraim A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Quantifying the value of information systems' (IS) contribution toa company is one of the biggest problems facing informationsystems managers.andP;  Years ago, it was easier to measure the valueof IS.andP;  IS budgets were smaller, systems were mostly centralizedand thus more easily measured, and the basic value of IS was seenas increased efficiency.andP;  In the 1980s IS budgets have ballooned,decentralization has skyrocketed, and IS is seen as playing abigger role in providing a competitive advantage to a business.andO;Assessing IS value requires examining at least three dimensions:time (current versus future), scope (individual versus enterprise)and focus (internal versus external).andP;  External focus is veryimportant, for it is concerned with how IS contributes to a firm'ssuccess.andP;  The most difficult dimension to measure is theenterprise-wide impact of IS.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Cost Benefit AnalysisInformation SystemsMeasurement TechniquesMISManagement ScienceManagement of EDPInformation Resources Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>